Pre-Game Insights: Australia have won four from four, while it's England who have spent the past fortnight circling the drain.
England have a 0.4% chance of reaching the knock-outs, but they aren't dead yet despite five losses in six.
Australia boast a pair of openers with three times as many centuries as England's entire lineup has contributed across six matches.
Ben Stokes has struggled significantly in this World Cup, being dismissed eight times in the first ten overs in 16 ODIs since early 2022.
Adam Zampa has grown in confidence with every subsequent outing, currently holding the best bowling figures among Australian bowlers with 16 wickets.
England might give opportunities to some of the players more likely to feature in the post-World Cup rebuild, such as Harry Brook and Gus Atkinson.
David Willey, who has confirmed his retirement from international cricket at the end of the tournament, needs six more wickets in a maximum of three games to reach 100 in ODIs.
Miscellaneous Highlights: This match will determine the participants for the 2025 Champions Trophy based on the final placings in this group stage.
The immediate tournament context is sure to be rolled into the wider, wilder narrative of an ancient and implacable rivalry.
Up to 15 of the 22 players on parade in Ahmedabad on Saturday will have played their part in an Ashes series in the English summer just gone.
The near-messianic sense of purpose that encapsulated England's Test summer has deserted them since the switch from red to white-ball cricket.
